## Configuration

Add the messaging modules to your `medusa-config.ts`:

```ts
modules: [
  {
    resolve: './modules/messaging',
  },
  {
    resolve: './modules/messaging-filters',
  },
  {
    resolve: './modules/messaging-redis',
    options: {
      redisUrl: process.env.REDIS_URL,
    },
  },
]
```

## Middlewares

Add the messaging middlewares to your `api/middlewares.ts`:

```ts
import { defineMiddlewares } from "@medusajs/medusa";
import { storeMessagingMiddlewares } from "./store/messages/middlewares";
import { vendorMessagingMiddlewares } from "./vendor/messages/middlewares";
import { adminMessagingMiddlewares } from "./admin/messages/middlewares";

export default defineMiddlewares({
  routes: [
    ...storeMessagingMiddlewares,
    ...vendorMessagingMiddlewares,
    ...adminMessagingMiddlewares,
  ],
});
```

If you already have a `middlewares.ts` file, merge the messaging middleware imports and spread them into your existing `routes` array.

## Environment Variables

The messaging block requires Redis for real-time delivery, rate limiting, and content filter cache invalidation:

```env
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379
```

## Database Migrations

After installing the block and adding the module configuration, generate and run the migrations:

```bash
npx medusa db:generate messaging
npx medusa db:generate messagingFilters
npx medusa db:migrate
```

